Stocks leap to record; S&P 500 tops 1,700
NEW YORK (MarketWatch) — U.S. stocks leapt on Thursday, with the S&P 500 surpassing 1,700 for the first time, after the Federal Reserve said it would continue stimulus and data showed jobless claims falling to a five-year low and a manufacturing index surging to a two-year high.
“Seventeen-hundred is our year-end target, so this has been faster and stronger than we expected,” said Marc Doss, regional chief investment officer at Wells Fargo Private Bank, referring to the S&P 500. Read: Main Street and Wall Street may be on a collision course.
After climbing 5% in July, its largest monthly jump since January, the S&P 500 index SPX, -0.57%  on Thursday rose 21.14 points, or 1.3%, to 1,706.87, clearing 1,700 for the first time.Read: S&P 500 at 1,700 is a yellow light for Wall Street.
Industrials led gains that included all of the S&P’s 10 sectors.
Also finishing at a record, the Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, -0.34%  rallied 128.48 points, or 0.8%, to 15,628.02, after rising to an intraday record of 15,650.69.
The Nasdaq Composite COMP, -0.78%  added 49.37 points, or 1.4%, to 3,675.74.
Wells Fargo’s Doss said Thursday’s economic data were “quite good” and the stock market appeared comfortable with the Federal Reserve starting to scale back its $85 billion in monthly bond purchases in September.
Stocks extended their gains after the Institute for Supply Management’s U.S. manufacturing index jumped to 55.4% in July from 50.9% in June.
“For manufacturing, the third quarter started on a strong footing and while it’s not assured of course, a reduction by the Fed in asset purchases in September seems even more likely than before,” Dan Greenhaus, chief global strategist at BTIG LLC, wrote in an emailed note.
Moving issues includedProcter & Gamble Co. PG, -3.27% shares of which rose 1.7% after the household-products maker projected 2013 earnings would climb at least as much as last year.
MetLife Inc. MET, +0.94% rose 6.3% after the life insurer reported quarterly operating earnings that beat estimates.
Yelp Inc. YELP, -0.40%  rallied 23% after the online-review site forecast third-quarter revenue that exceeded Wall Street estimates.
J.C. Penney Co. JCP, +0.00%  ended down 0.1% after the department-store operator dismissed a reportabout CIT Group Inc. CIT, +2.30%  halting financing to its suppliers, saying it had reassurances from the commercial lender.
For every stock falling, nearly two gained on the New York Stock Exchange, where almost 755 million shares exchanged hands. Composite volume neared 3.7 billion.
The 10-year Treasury note yield US:10_YEAR climbed 13 basispoints to 2.712% and the dollar DXY, +0.31%  gained against the currencies of major U.S. trading partners.
Gold futures fell for a third session, with the December contract GCZ3, +0.15%  losing $1.80 to settle at $1,311.20 an ounce.
In addition to the ISM data, investors received upbeat news on the U.S. labor market.
Applications for unemployment benefits fell by 19,000 to 326,000 last week, the lowest since January 2008, from a revised 345,000 the week before, the Labor Department reported.
The weekly data come a day ahead of the nonfarm payrolls report for July. See Economic Calendar.
“The pressure will again intensify on the FOMC if today’s ISM and claims data are followed by a good payroll report tomorrow. For the economy, the test will be can it handle higher rates and the same needs to be said for stocks at these levels,” emailed Peter Boockvar, chief market analyst at the Lindsey Group LLC.
In another report, U.S. construction projectsfell 0.6% in June, with May construction spending upwardly revised to 1.3% growth.
China’s official PMI for manufacturing climbed to 50.3 in July from 50.1 the prior month, with activity rising as new orders increased. An HSBC report on Chinese manufacturing was more downbeat, declining to 47.7 last month from 48.2 in June.
Markit’s euro-zone manufacturing PMI rose to 50.3 last month from June’s 48.8, surpassing the threshold for growth for the first time in two years.
The reports illustrated mild growth for the global economy, helping maintain the belief that central banks would continue stimulus policies.
The European Central Bank held interest rates at 0.5%, with ECB President Mario Draghi repeating rates would remain at record lowsfor an extended period. The Bank of England also held rates at 0.5%.